  "text": "The re-assessment of waiting list controls indicated that satisfaction self-ratings on the CoPM were not stable prior to the intervention. It is possible that satisfaction with performance is a particularly subjective index, influenced by various factors (e.g. mood state or treatment expectations). Therefore, whilst this index remains important in client-centred outcome assessment, the lack of stability prior to an intervention suggests that changes following an intervention need to be interpreted with caution. A more conservative statistical approach, such as an individual reliable change index, may be warranted to identify genuine and reliable improvement [CITATION_1] . Furthermore, an individual reliable change index may be usefully applied to examine clinically meaningful change on the CoPM, as opposed to interpreting change using the 2-point difference as a general guide [CITATION_2] .",
